reviews.review_text:
Crispy high end.. Hi GD fans,  

I noticed this show was just uploaded and many thanks to our great crew of Charlie Miller and Co. for procuring these tapes.  I'm not really too familiar with this show but after a little digging, it seems that many fans like this show.  I "spot" listened to a few sources including the soundboard.  I'm not fond of the soundboard, granted it is not via the master but sometimes many soundboards are not "broadcast quality".  Many 80s soundboards are from Master Cassettes as reel tapes and the usage of reel machines became more expensive, but thanks to really HQ cassette decks with metal bias, it's possible to get a really good cassette source.  I've heard that the 10-14-83 Dick's Picks was sourced from cassette?

However, I like this source from Streeter with Senn 421's which are a great universal microphone.  Sure, they can be a little bit brittle on the high end but if done well; they can yield a nice balance of sound.  Many of the other audience sources are a bit grainy and over modulated with harmonic distortion.  It sucks , that we don't have a nice PCM digital source as the PA sound is really good which is evident on most audience sources.  Indianapolis was the cornerstone for BMG inc. which was the largest distributor of music , mostly LPs and cassette of the time, so maybe; the GD wanted to sound extra good to get on those Columbia Record House deals... why not sell more LPs?
